Q: Mapstruct Optional into Optional A: <p>I found workaround for that.</p>
<pre><code>@Mapper
public interface UserMapper {
    // Dummy type
    record User(int p1) {
    }

    // Dummy type
    record UserModel(int p2) {
    }

    //Method you want
    default Optional&lt;User&gt; map(Optional&lt;UserModel&gt; userModel) {
        return userModel.flatMap(x -&gt; mapWrapped(x).value());
    }


    //Your actual mapping
    @Mapping(target = &quot;p1&quot;, source = &quot;p2&quot;)
    User mapInternal(UserModel userModel);



    //First layer of wrapping
    @Mapping(target = &quot;value&quot;, source = &quot;userModel&quot;, qualifiedByName = &quot;wrap&quot;)
    Wrapper&lt;User&gt; mapWrapped(UserModel userModel);

    //Second layer of wrapping
    @Named(&quot;wrap&quot;)
    default &lt;T&gt; Optional&lt;T&gt; wrap(T string) {
        return Optional.ofNullable(string);
    }

    // crutch
    record Wrapper&lt;T&gt;(Optional&lt;T&gt; value) {
    }
}

</code></pre>
<p>It only useful if you need <code>map</code> to be accessible from other mappings, otherwise it way easier for it to just return <code>User</code> and wrap it into <code>Optional</code> later.</p>

Q: Restrict nuget package updates to current versions for some packages A: <p>I don't have a package.config. (VS 2019, .NET Core 3.1) What I did instead was changing the .csproj of the project which had the package which I needed to stop showing up for updates.</p>
<p>In my case it was EPPlus, and I wrapped the version number within square brackets.</p>
<pre><code>&lt;ItemGroup&gt;
    &lt;PackageReference Include=&quot;EPPlus&quot; Version=&quot;[4.5.3.3]&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/ItemGroup&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>After that, it stopped showing up on the Updates tab in Nuget Package Manager.</p>
<p>And it doesn't give any option to update from anywhere else too. (Installed tab, Nuget for the solution, etc)</p>
<p>You'll need to restart VS to get rid of the yellow triangles next to the packages.</p>
<p>There is a <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/nuget/concepts/package-versioning?tabs=semver20sort#version-ranges" rel="nofollow noreferrer">Nuget Package Version Reference</a> documentation.</p>

Q: How to overload the subscript operator in C++? A: <p>Basically...</p>
<pre><code>value&amp; operator[](size_t index) { ... }
const value&amp; operator[](size_t index) const { ... }
</code></pre>
<p>Just have each return (by reference) the value at that index.  The &quot;index&quot; you use can be any single value - e.g. an int, string, knock yourself out....</p>

Q: Flipping line of 4-Byte pixels horizontally A: <p>Based on Chayim Friedmans answer <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/a/79849515/6659960">https://stackoverflow.com/a/79849515/6659960</a>, I found a solution which passes my test, and is actually just an even smaller and simpler version of Friedmans answer:</p>
<pre class="lang-rust prettyprint-override"><code>fn flip_line(line_bytes: &amp;mut [u8]) {
    let (line_pixels, _) = line_bytes.as_chunks_mut::&lt;BYTES_PER_PIXEL&gt;();
    for i in 0..PIXELS_PER_SIDE / 2 {
        line_pixels.swap(i, line_pixels.len() - i - 1);
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p>First thought, if I looked superficially at the code out of context would be: &quot;Oh no, this creates copies everywhere, so the results have to be copied back, and then the speed advantage is completely gone&quot;, but no: This does all actually in-place, backed by <code>line_bytes</code>.
And it's even a tiny bit faster than the unsafe code.</p>
<p>So, thanks, the original answer had 2 bugs, but fixing them wasn't hard, and the fixed solution is far better than mine.</p>
